  "figure-25-26": (
    caption: [Unusual reproductive strategies of anurans. A, Female South American pygmy marsupial frog, *Flectonotus pygmaeus*, carries developing larvae in a dorsal pouch. B, Female Surinam frog carries eggs embedded in specialized brooding pouches on the dorsum; froglets emerge and swim away when development is complete. C, Male poison arrow frog, *Phyllobates bicolor*, carries tadpoles adhering to its back. D, Tadpoles of a male Darwin’s frog, *Rhinoderma darwinii*, develop into froglets in its vocal pouch. When ready to emerge, a froglet crawls into the parent’s mouth, which the parent opens to allow the froglet’s escape.],
